questiontext.text:
Consider the following graph, given that the red curve is a cubic, write down the equations of the two simultaneous equations and give one solution of the equations.

 

 

Eqn1: y =[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]

Eqn2: y = [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]

Solution: \(x = \)[[input:ans31]] [[validation:ans31]], \(y =\)[[input:ans32]] [[validation:ans32]][[feedback:prt3]]

generalfeedback.text:
Reading the curves from the graph gives:

eqn1: \(y={@ta1@}\)

eqn2: \(y = {@ta2@}\).

The solutions to the simultaneous equations are the coordinates of the point of intersection of the two lines. Hence one solution is:

\(x = {@ta31@}\), \(y = {@ta32@}\). Another solution is \(x = {@x2@}\), \(y = {@y2@}\) and the third solution (which we can't see on the graph) is \(x = {@x3@}, y = {@y3@}\).
